## Overview

Headers are fundamental markdown elements that create a hierarchical structure in your documentation. They range from H1 (largest) to H6 (smallest) and help organize content into scannable sections.

## Syntax

Headers are created using hash symbols (`#`) followed by a space and your heading text. The number of hash symbols determines the heading level:

### Headers

<TabGroup>
  <Tab title="Preview">
  # H1 Header
  ## H2 Header
  ### H3 Header
  #### H4 Header
  ##### H5 Header
  ###### H6 Header
  </Tab>

  <Tab title="Syntax">
  ```markdown
  # H1 Header
  ## H2 Header
  ### H3 Header
  #### H4 Header
  ##### H5 Header
  ###### H6 Header
  ```
  </Tab>
</TabGroup>

## Heading Hierarchy

<Callout type="warning">
Always maintain proper heading hierarchy. Skip levels (e.g., H2 to H4) disrupts document structure and affects accessibility.
</Callout>

**Correct hierarchy:**
```markdown
## Main Section (H2)
### Subsection (H3)
#### Detail (H4)
```

**Incorrect hierarchy:**
```markdown
## Main Section (H2)
#### Detail (H4) ❌ Skips H3
```

## Best Practices

<Steps>
<Step title="Start with H2 for page content">
Reserve H1 for the page title defined in frontmatter. Begin your content sections with H2 headers.

<CodeSnippet language="markdown">
---
title: "Your Page Title" # This becomes H1
---

## First Section (H2)
Content here...

### Subsection (H3)
More content...
</CodeSnippet>
</Step>

<Step title="Use descriptive, keyword-rich headers">
Write headers that clearly describe the section content and include relevant keywords for search optimization.

<CodeGroup>
<CodeSnippet language="markdown" title="Good">
## Authentication with API Keys
## Configuring Environment Variables
</CodeSnippet>

<CodeSnippet language="markdown" title="Avoid">
## Setup
## Details
</CodeSnippet>
</CodeGroup>
</Step>

<Step title="Keep headers concise">
Aim for 3-7 words per header. Long headers reduce scannability.

<Callout type="tip">
If your header exceeds 10 words, consider breaking the content into multiple sections or simplifying the header text.
</Callout>
</Step>
</Steps>

